<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/books-arts <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/books-arts" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 18 日星期二 04:08:07 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[‘Theoderic the Great’ Review: The Warrior King]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>狄奥多里克的权力源于他在战斗中的成功。他徒手杀死了一位国王，并用剑将另一位对手切成两半。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590085802732813236"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818743?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">狄奥多里克大帝，东哥特人国王。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：德阿戈斯蒂尼来自盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590085802732813236"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">凯尔·哈珀</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:10 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>如果有一个罗马版的《1066 and All That》（这部讽刺英国历史的作品），那么 476 年肯定会成为我们集体历史想象中那些可疑的大胆线条之一。就在那时，罗马最后一位皇帝罗穆卢斯·奥古斯都鲁在西方被废黜。在他十个月的统治期间，一方面是古代。另一方面，中世纪。</p><p>那么，从 493 年统治意大利直至 526 年去世的东哥特国王狄奥多里克大帝又将何去何从呢？在这位讲哥特语的武士的统治下，斗兽场仍然充斥着观众的喧嚣，清脆的山水仍然流过渡槽，卡西奥多罗斯和波爱提乌斯等拉丁文学巨擘仍然在元老院任职。</p><p>汉斯·乌尔里希·维默的《狄奥多里克大帝：哥特人之王，罗马人的统治者》是对这位杰出领袖的生活和时代的不朽探索。这是自威廉·恩斯林 (Wilhelm Ensslin) 1947 年传记以来对该主题最重要的论述，而且由于维默先生的书（这里是约翰·诺尔·狄龙 (John Noël Dillon) 流畅的英文译本）在广度和复杂性方面超越了前作，作者可以声称自己写出了我们对狄奥多里克最好的简介。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a1de8862-2513-4f6a-a639-1ba2a75ef33f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>狄奥多里克的故事是史诗般的，也是不可思议的。他于 453 年或 454 年出生在争议不断的多瑙河边境地区（可能位于现在的奥地利东部），父亲是一位精锐的哥特战士，母亲的背景却默默无闻。阿提拉最近去世后，狄奥多里克所属的哥特部落刚刚摆脱匈奴人的长期统治。 461 年，男孩狄奥多里克被运送到君士坦丁堡作为条约的保险。他在罗马帝国的大都市度过了近十年的青少年时期。</p><p>维默强调，狄奥多里克的权力与其说是源自他显赫的血统，也不是源自哥特式对王室合法性的尊重，而是源自他作为一名战士的成功。作为一个暴发户王子，他亲手杀死了萨尔马提亚国王巴拜。作为一支可怕的哥特军队的指挥官，他被证明是东罗马帝国善变的盟友，而东罗马帝国的皇帝本身并不是忠诚的典范。 480年代初期，他被罗马人任命为总司令。几年之内，他就围攻君士坦丁堡。</p><p>如果他的职业生涯就此结束，狄奥多里克的名字将属于动荡不安的五世纪杰出的雇佣军军阀之一。但命运眷顾勇敢者，狄奥多里克还有更远大的抱负。 488 年，他与大约 100,000 名追随者（男人、女人和儿童）一起乘坐武装车队出发，从多瑙河沿岸（位于现在的保加利亚）前往意大利，踏上一段充满不确定性的旅程。他们的目标是推翻罗穆卢斯·奥古斯特鲁斯的废黜者奥多亚塞，并为自己找到一个永久的家。狄奥多里克将奥多亚塞和他的军队逼入了拉文纳的主要据点，两人签署了一份旨在分享权力的条约。该条约持续了大约 10 天，之后狄奥多里克亲手将他的对手劈成两半（维默先生告诉我们，“用一剑，将他从锁骨到臀部切开”）。从这样的血腥开始，意大利出现了一代和平。</p><p>维默先生的调查之所以如此丰富，是因为他对古代黄昏研究的掌握。狄奥多里克的统治几乎切入了这一时期学者之间每一次重大辩论的核心。他笔下的东哥特人本质上是日耳曼部落，还是种族身份是一个被偶然的权力动态重新配置的虚构？</p><p>对于埃尔兰根-纽伦堡大学古代史教授维默来说，东哥特人是一个“暴力社会”，其物质基础是战争和掠夺。但作者认识到，追随狄奥多里克踏上意大利冒险之旅的群众是一群拥有共同历史和文化的民族，这使他们与意大利当地人区别开来，并拉近了他们与其他群体的距离，例如定居在西班牙和高卢的西哥特人。</p><p>维默先生对狄奥多里克国内外政策的主线的阐述令人信服。在国内，狄奥多里克追求哥特人和罗马人之间的功能专业化。前者是战士（如果也是地主），后者是平民。双轨政府反映了这种基本的分工。狄奥多里克寻求互补，而不是融合。</p><p>在国外，他寻求东罗马首都的合法性以及后罗马西部的稳定。通过战略条约和汪达尔人、西哥特人、法兰克人、勃艮第人和其他人之间惊人的联姻联盟网络，狄奥多里克成为君士坦丁堡以西最强大的统治者。由于机会主义的扩张，他控制了巴尔干半岛的大片地区、高卢南部的大部分地区和（名义上的）伊比利亚半岛。在六世纪初，法兰克王国是否会变得更加持久和重要并不明显。</p><p>如果说这本书有一个弱点的话，那就是试图解释狄奥多里克的成就如何如此迅速而彻底地解开的谜团。维默先生很好地描述了动荡的最后几年，包括在狄奥多里克的命令下处决波伊提乌斯的永恒污点。但关于狄奥多里克统治的后果却太少了。一场继承危机，然后被查士丁尼重新征服，接着是黑死病的毁灭性到来（维默先生低估了这一点），使东哥特人的实验结束了不光彩的结局。众所周知，在意大利的考古记录中，哥特式存在的物质痕迹很少。哥特人的彻底消亡和相对隐匿与一代人之后到来的伦巴第人形成鲜明对比。他们用武力从罗马人手中夺取了意大利半岛的大部分地区，并统治了两个世纪——没有一个像狄奥多里克一半伟大的领导人。</p><p>通过某种阴暗的过程，狄奥多里克的记忆在伯尔尼的迪特里希的传说中被保留或扭曲。再后来，他的遗产成为现代德国身份观念的密码。但在维默先生冷静的传记中，我们有机会看到一个不容易符合古代或中世纪简单概念的人和时刻。</p><p><em>哈珀先生是俄克拉荷马大学教授，也是圣达菲研究所分形学院的成员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Ballad of Darren’ by Blur Review: Reflective British Rock]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Blur 仍然由 Gorillaz 联合创作人 Damon Albarn 领导，在中断期后回归，比以往任何时候都更加自信，推出了第九张录音室专辑，该专辑有利于歌曲创作的坚实基础。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093961998203380"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818269?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">模糊</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：鲁本·巴斯蒂安·刘易斯</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093961998203380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马克·理查森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 5:15 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ballad-of-darren-by-blur-review-reflective-british-rock-547ae7f3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Blur 已经经历了很长一段时间，似乎或多或少已经解体，四位成员——主唱兼吉他手达蒙·阿尔本 (Damon Albarn)、主音吉他手格雷厄姆·考克森 (Graham Coxon)、贝斯手亚历克斯·詹姆斯 (Alex James) 和鼓手戴夫·朗特里 (Dave Rowntree)——之间的关系是出了名的紧张。在 1994 年的“Parklife”和 1999 年的“13”等发行的专辑中，这种紧张感在经典专辑中得到了体现，这些专辑从讽刺和真诚的角度来探讨英国生活。在贯穿 2003 年“Think Tank”的这一系列顶级素材中，乐队不断进行实验，从精益的低保真摇滚转向管弦乐盛况，再到带有电子色彩的美妙音乐。尽管 Blur 在 90 年代中期处于鼎盛时期是英伦流行音乐的基石，但与当时的大多数同行不同的是，它一直在不断前进，直到乐队决定暂时转向其他领域。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818266?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p>在过去的 20 年里，Blur 从 Albarn 先生的主要出路变成了他只有在情绪高涨时才会重访的场所，而那些时光在英国受到了欢乐的庆祝。就在一周前，乐队在拥有 90,000 个座位的伦敦温布利体育场两晚门票全部售空。但在美国，这支重要且富有冒险精神的摇滚乐队从未在商业上取得突破。 Blur 2015 年排行榜最高的专辑《The Magic Whip》排名第 24 位，恰好与 Gorillaz 的八张录音室 LP 中排行榜最低的专辑排名相同，Albarn 先生与视觉艺术家 Jamie Hewlett 共同负责该项目。后者的几张唱片已跻身前五名。Blur 的第九张专辑《The Ballad of Darren》（Parlophone/华纳）于周五发行，距离最新的 Gorillaz LP《Cracker Island》发行仅五个月，这提供了一个有趣的比较点。</p><p>这是 Blur 最简单、最直接的完整版本——它在强调基础知识的同时，对声音的华丽程度也很轻。如果风险意识不足，Blur 可以用一流的歌曲创作和令人印象深刻的经济来弥补。开场曲“The Ballad”有一段可爱的钢琴旋律和适合其标题的节奏，而这首歌本身在一定程度上是关于变老和调整一个人的期望。阿尔本先生唱出了当“歌谣为你而来”时所发生的事情，他使用更安静、更具反思性的形式来比喻死亡，但只是眨了眨眼睛。</p><p>这是一种有趣而苦乐参半的情绪——下面的曲目“St.查尔斯广场，”完全颠倒了。这是专辑中唯一一首不折不扣的摇滚乐——以乐队的标准来看是相当柔和的一首——而且它具有吸引人的冲击力，还有考克森先生优美的锯齿状吉他副歌。 “每一代人都有其镀金的装腔作势者，”阿尔本先生唱道，如果他在 1995 年发表这句话，那么他的歌词会产生截然不同的效果。那时，这可能是对一个嫉妒的仇恨者的讽刺。现在，它看起来既有趣又懂事，因为艺术家早已不再需要关心别人的想法了。</p><p> 《达伦之歌》中的许多歌词既异想天开，又令人厌倦，暗示着友谊和浪漫似乎已经崩溃，但却是在孤立的地方发生的。其他人则在政治崩溃和关系破裂的场景之间切换，但阿尔本先生以诗意和智慧的眼光表达了如此沉重的情感。 “你现在在哪里？”他在庄严的“俄罗斯弦乐”开头问道，后来唱道：“公寓楼轰然倒塌/戴上耳机你就听不到那么多。”在第六首歌《自恋者》中，阿尔本先生首先说他看着镜子，看到“那么多人站在那里”，他似乎在回顾自己的失败，并为自己下次做得更好而打气。他在和弦进行和和声结构上呈现出断裂而令人愉快的有趣线条，接近完美——每一个微妙的音乐转折都既令人舒适又熟悉，又令人惊讶地新颖。</p><p>考克森先生的吉他作品自始至终都是引人注目且高效的。在《再见阿尔伯特》中，他在一条随着展开而破裂的扭曲引导线和令人想起罗伯特·弗里普的梦幻氛围的气体嗡嗡声之间滑动。结尾的“高地”有一个最后的部分，它不断构建，直到它似乎要在噪音的火球中爆炸；然后声音突然中断，专辑就这样结束了。 《The Ballad of Darren》是一张简短的唱片——10首曲目，36分钟——而且在很多地方听起来都与《Cracker Island》非常相似。这两个版本都避免了极端，淡化了过去的实验，并首先展示了精心制作的歌曲的力量。虽然很难不错过 Blur 在千禧年巅峰时期令人眼花缭乱的傲慢，但乐队致力于将其发展到今天的程度，这本身就是自信的标志。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。理查森是《华尔街日报》的摇滚和流行音乐评论家。在 Twitter 上关注他@MarkRichardson。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 21:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ballad-of-darren-by-blur-review-reflective-british-rock-547ae7f3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ballad-of-darren-by-blur-review-reflective-british-rock-547ae7f3<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukrainian Strike Disables Bridge Between Crimea and Russia]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>莫斯科称基辅使用海军无人机仅袭击了从半岛到俄罗斯的公路<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059347"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=562ED18C-1F7B-4F97-8EEF-A3B2EE57B4D8&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">连接俄罗斯和被占领的克里米亚半岛的刻赤大桥在乌克兰的一次袭击中被毁。俄罗斯表示，基辅使用两架海军无人机袭击了这座桥，该桥是为在乌克兰作战的俄罗斯军队提供补给的重要路线。照片：路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059347"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/yaroslav-trofimov" itemprop="url" rel="author">雅罗斯拉夫·特罗菲莫夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 4:04（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>乌克兰的一次袭击使连接俄罗斯与被占领的克里米亚半岛的唯一公路桥瘫痪，再次打击了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>总统统治的一个主要象征，并限制了俄罗斯对乌克兰南部<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">前线的</a>供应。</p><p>俄罗斯副总理马拉特·库斯努林 (Marat Khusnullin) 表示，可能需要到 9 月中旬才能恢复大桥上的部分双向货运交通，并到 11 月才能完全重建这座 12 英里长的结构。</p><p>据俄罗斯国家反恐委员会称，基辅当地时间周一凌晨3点左右使用两架海军无人机袭击了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/attack-on-russias-kerch-bridge-hits-crucial-link-for-crimea-and-troops-11665342526?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这座桥</a>。乌克兰媒体援引政府消息人士的话称，海军无人机也参与其中。</p><p>乌克兰 SBU 情报部门发言人 Artem Degtyarenko 告诉乌克兰国际文传电讯社，有关袭击组织方式的所有细节将在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-gears-up-to-hit-russiansand-show-west-it-can-win-89c43105?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰获胜</a>后公布。乌克兰总统泽连斯基的顾问米哈伊洛·波多利亚克表示：“任何用于运送俄罗斯大规模谋杀工具的非法建筑都必然是短暂的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="908" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d0587735-f4b2-487c-afa7-3aaa47c344b7-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>周一的袭击正值克里米亚旅游旺季，除了给俄罗斯的战争努力造成巨大的后勤障碍外，还对普京的威望造成了又一次打击。这座桥是2014年俄罗斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vladimir-putin-signs-treaty-to-annex-crimea-1395144516?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">吞并克里米亚</a>后耗资40亿美元建造的，它已成为普京努力洗刷他所说的苏联解体给俄罗斯带来的耻辱的主要象征。普京于2018年亲自揭幕。</p><p>去年十月，就在普京生日后几小时，乌克兰已经<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/major-explosion-hits-the-bridge-between-crimea-and-russia-halting-traffic-11665215052?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">损坏了这座桥</a>一次。当时，大桥的两个道路部分中只有一个发生塌陷，数小时后第二个双车道部分恢复了交替交通。</p><p>库斯努林周一视察了现场并向普京汇报，他说大桥的支柱没有被损坏，但其中一个跨度必须完全更换。他说，一个平行的跨度已经移动了大约 70-80 厘米，但仍然支撑在一根柱子上。维修人员正在尝试将其修复到位，并将首先使用重达三吨（相当于一辆客车的重量）的车辆进行测试，然后使用重达五吨（相当于一辆普通救护车的重量）的车辆进行测试，希望能够重新开放该车道以供有限使用。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818349?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一架军用直升机飞越刻赤大桥受损部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>库斯努林说，这座独立的铁路桥在十月份遭受了严重损坏，但在周一的爆炸中仅受到轻微损坏。对于军事供应更为重要的铁路服务已经恢复。</p><p>白宫国家安全委员会发言人约翰·柯比表示，他怀疑这次袭击会对俄罗斯的作战能力产生重大影响，并指出俄罗斯还有许多其他方式为克里米亚半岛的部队提供补给。</p><p>俄罗斯称两名平民在桥上死亡。 “这是基辅政权的又一起恐怖行为，”普京在与政府官员就袭击后果举行的视频会议结束时表示。 “俄罗斯将会做出回应。国防部正在准备相应的建议。”</p><p>普京对十月份的袭击作出回应，下令对乌克兰民用基础设施进行<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-ukraine-survived-russias-mission-to-turn-off-the-lights-winter-is-over-and-were-still-here-8668c5f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一波又一波的袭击</a>，旨在剥夺乌克兰人在冬季的电力、供暖和供水。这些攻击虽然导致轮流停电，但最终未能摧毁该国的能源系统，同时促使美国及其盟国向乌克兰提供现代防空系统，例如爱国者和SAMP-T反导弹系统。</p><p>乌克兰上个月在乌克兰南部发动攻势，但由于其部队面临大片雷区和防御工事以及俄罗斯武装直升机，因此只取得了有限的进展。最近几周，基辅利用英国和法国提供的“风暴之影”和“头皮” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-deadly-new-missile-was-created-to-hit-saddam-hussein-in-his-bathtub-75e04412?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">巡航导弹</a>，大大扩展了其射程，重点摧毁俄罗斯武器库、指挥中心和后勤节点。</p><p>上个月，“风暴之影”袭击了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-strikes-bridge-supplying-russian-troops-56564b0b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">琼哈尔大桥，</a>克里米亚和乌克兰南部之间的主要连接被切断了十天，这条替代道路现在已成为俄罗斯的主要生命线。琼哈尔大桥于7月3日重新开放。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818163?width=700&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">据报道，这张图片显示了连接俄罗斯和克里米亚的桥梁受损情况。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：OSTOROZHNO NOVOSTI/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>去年秋天，乌克兰成功地运用了这一战略，当时对第聂伯河上的桥梁和其他后勤节点的袭击将俄罗斯军队赶出了被占领的南部城市赫尔松。</p><p>周一的袭击发生当天，俄罗斯、土耳其、联合国和乌克兰之间允许乌克兰港口出口谷物和其他食品的协议即将到期。该协议一年前在伊斯坦布尔达成，此后定期更新。袭击发生后，俄罗斯表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将退出该协议</a>，但谈判仍在继续，土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安表示，他计划与普京讨论延期事宜。自去年8月该协议生效以来，乌克兰出口了超过3200万吨粮食。</p><p>去年二月，随着普京入侵乌克兰，与克里米亚的民用航空联系中断。通过乌克兰南部赫尔松、扎波罗热和顿涅茨克地区被占领地区的车辙道路与俄罗斯的替代连接非常复杂，而且在某些地区相对靠近前线。</p><p>由于数万名游客滞留在克里米亚，俄罗斯政府表示将放松边境检查，并取消被占领的乌克兰南部替代道路上的宵禁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="435" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818168?width=700&amp;height=435" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">交通暂停后，警察封锁了通往刻赤海峡一座桥梁的道路。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Sergei Malgavko/TASS/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给雅罗斯拉夫·特罗菲莫夫 (yaroslav Trofimov)： <a href="mailto:yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 20:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge- Between- Russia-and-crimea-damaging-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge- Between- Russia-and-crimea-damaging-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88<author><![CDATA[Yaroslav Trofimov]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>重型建筑</category><category>桥梁建设</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>重型建筑</category><category>桥梁建设</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Divorce Parties Are a New Hot Invite. ‘It Sort of Ended Up as a Really Fun Funeral.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着社会广泛接受破裂的婚姻，许多刚刚离婚的人更有勇气对自己进行抨击。 &#39;错误结束&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814552?width=1000&amp;height=562" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>视频：瓦夏·科洛图沙<span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001042895"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001042895"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lane-florsheim" itemprop="url" rel="author">莱恩·弗洛舍姆</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web
          bigtophero
"></div><p>布兰迪·斯特勒斯 (Brandi Stellers) 离婚后，她邀请密友参加五月的一场晚会。她调制了招牌鸡尾酒，挂上了“再见费利西亚”的横幅，并分发假玫瑰花瓣并抛向空中。</p><p>派对装饰品包括一张从中间撕下来的一对企鹅的照片。</p><p> “我把企鹅撕成两半，因为企鹅是一夫一妻制的鸟类，应该终身交配，”她说。 “好吧，我不再是你的企鹅了。”</p><p>新近离婚的人正在为自己举办井喷式的狂欢，以纪念他们从不幸的婚姻中解放出来，就像反向单身派对一样。在俄亥俄州哥伦布市一家云计算公司工作的斯特勒斯说：“我想庆祝的不是离婚，而是一个新的篇章，与那些我爱的人一起庆祝，他们都希望我过得最好。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="803" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817952?width=639&amp;height=803" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">布兰迪·斯特勒斯在她的离婚后晚会上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布兰迪·斯特勒斯</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在历史的大部分时间里，离婚并不是一件被全世界吹捧的事件。现在，文化转变正在进行。美国的离婚率一直在下降，但那些离婚的人却可以更自由地宣扬自己的分手。盖洛普民意调查显示，认为离婚在道德上可以接受的美国成年人数量已创历史新高。</p><p> “由于社会压力和刻板印象，离婚曾经是一件令人羞耻的事情，”离婚律师妮可·索多玛（Nicole Sodoma）说，她就这个话题写了《请不要说对不起》一书。 “但今天，人们真的决定消除这种社会耻辱，转而接受离婚作为我们中的一些人经历的人生的另一个阶段。”</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ETSY" class="company-name">Etsy</a>和亚马逊上，品牌出售 splitsville 的周边商品，包括“End of an Error”腰带、“Thank U Next”玫瑰金箔气球和“I do.我做到了。我完成了”T 恤。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PINS" class="">Pinterest</a>数据洞察全球总监 Swasti Sarna 表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>在分享创意的在线平台 Pinterest 上，“搜索趋势表明人们正在以新的视角看待离婚”。</p><p> 2022 年 6 月，Pinterest 上“离婚派对游戏”的搜索量同比增长 80%，“离婚蛋糕”的搜索量同比增长 50%。 Pinterest 的数据显示，离婚派对装饰创意（35%）和“离婚礼物”（30%）的搜索量也出现了激增。</p><p> “这只是一种感觉，我并不为此感到羞耻，”曼哈顿和布鲁克林的房地产经纪人纳丁·亚当森 (Nadine Adamson) 说，她举办了一场离婚派对。 “我认为在纽约结婚超过 10 年——我结婚 12 年——是一个巨大的成功。”</p><p>亚当森让朋友从洛杉矶飞往纽约，他们预订了她结婚时住过的酒店套房。 “在同一家酒店欣赏同样的景色，感觉就像以一种非常美妙的方式结束了，”她说。</p><p>他们四人在套房里烧鼠尾草，以消除负面情绪，在房间里放满气球，出去吃饭，然后过夜。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="696" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817050?width=700&amp;height=696" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">纳丁·亚当森 (Nadine Adamson) 在她的离婚派对上，在她参加婚礼的酒店房间里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：克里斯塔·蕾妮</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>亚当森还继续在 Instagram 上发布话题标签#divorceparty，并不是因为她一直扔它们，而是为了突出她的新生活，比如用舒适的燃木壁炉升级她的上流社会。</p><p> “我猜离婚派对是一回事？”几个月前，一位 Reddit 用户发表了一篇帖子，吸引了近 4,000 条评论。海报上有一张来自一对正在举办联合派对的离婚夫妇的邀请函的照片。 “另外也欢迎——我们的也会在那里！”它说。</p><p>加拿大艾伯塔省的心理健康辅导员克里斯·马克斯 (Kris Marks) 表示，当一位朋友邀请他庆祝离婚时，他最初感到很矛盾。马克斯也是前夫的朋友，他认为他不知道这个聚会。</p><p> “我有很多想法，比如，我们应该庆祝承诺的结束吗？”马克斯说。 “我反复思考，得出的结论是，是的，婚姻制度就是这样，但如果你选择摆脱它，那是一件很难的事情，应该庆祝一个新的开始。我完全赞成它。”</p><p>他的结婚 12 年的朋友举办了一顿聚餐，然后一行人出去镇上过夜。 “这是我和另一个男人，也许还有 10 个女人，就像是单身派对上墙上的一只苍蝇，”他说。马克斯给他的朋友买了一个月的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dating-apps-paid-memberships-tinder-raya-hinge-11664984612?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Bumble Premium</a>作为礼物。</p><p>一些企业迎合新近离婚的男性。例如，Stripe Street Studio 是一家成立于 2020 年的设计公司，专门帮助离婚和单身男性建立住房。该公司表示，在 Pinterest 上，现在流行的流行语“离婚爸爸审美”的搜索量 6 月份比去年同期增长了近 300%。</p><p>不过，有传闻称，举行彻底离婚游行的女性多于男性。</p><p> “作为一个男人，我们不称之为离婚派对，我们称之为‘我们去喝酒吧，’马克斯解释道。 “我们只是以不同的方式应对。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817046?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">妮可·索多玛 (Nicole Sodoma) 离婚后，买了一辆老式汽车，以 1998 年浪漫喜剧《斯特拉如何找回她的魅力》的名字命名为斯特拉 (Stella)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Darius Evans/DME Imagery</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>现在，人们可以找到帮助离婚者补充物资的登记网站，因为只有一半的夫妇得到了意大利面机、香料架或 Le Creuset 炊具。</p><p>奥利维亚·德莱森·豪厄尔 (Olivia Dreizen Howell) 于 2019 年分居后，一直住在婚姻住所，但婚姻住所突然变得空荡荡的。 “我的一半东西都不见了，”她说，其他物品都是她婚礼登记处的充满情感的物品。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817051?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥利维亚·德莱森·豪厄尔签署离婚文件。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Fresh Starts 登记处</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，她和姐姐 Jenny Dreizen 在 2021 年为有同样经历的人们创立了 Fresh Starts 网站。</p><p>该公司帮助新婚夫妇建立礼物登记处，为新家的特定房间补充库存。最受欢迎的登记项目是厨房和浴室。他们还提供专家网络，例如房地产经纪人、宽恕教练和帮助策划离婚派对的离婚导乐。</p><p> 《艾米丽·波斯特礼仪：百年纪念版》一书的合著者莉齐·波斯特表示，艾米丽·波斯特研究所目前并不认为离婚当事人或离婚后登记是合适的。</p><p>她说：“离婚后与朋友们聚在一起，找到一种方法来结束这一章，感觉良好，这是一件非常令人支持的事情。” “我认为称其为离婚派对感觉有点不切实际。”</p><p>纽约的法律助理艾莉森·麦克怀特 (Allison McWhite) 表示，筹划自己的离婚派对给她带来了一种掌控感。 “很长一段时间以来，似乎有什么事情发生在我身上，向我冲来，而不是我去处理它，”她说。</p><p>她在朋友的公寓里举行了庆祝活动，音乐录影带被投影到墙上，黑色气球散落在地板上，烛台上的蜡滴在装有烛台的空酒瓶上。一个白色蛋糕上涂着樱桃红色的糖霜，上面写着“刚刚离婚”。麦克怀特 (McWhite) 身穿黑色蕾丝透明连衣裙，涂着红色口红，身穿毛皮大衣，符合<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/forget-wedding-dresses-divorce-style-has-arrived-11612616414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">20 世纪 50 年代离婚时尚</a>派对着装要求。 （想想玛丽莲·梦露 1954 年与乔·迪马吉奥离婚时的情景，当时她穿着小黑裙、脚踩高跟鞋、戴着白手套去法院。） </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/9c101278-b1d5-4ed6-915b-14735a357de8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>客人们跳舞到凌晨，庆祝她新生活的开始。</p><p> “这最终成为一场非常有趣的葬礼，”麦克怀特说。</p><p>对于一些离婚者来说，试图庆祝可能会适得其反，让人感觉像是在提醒他们失去亲人。</p><p> “当你离婚时，你就失去了一半的朋友，”伦敦的离婚律师阿伊莎·瓦尔达格 (Ayesha Vardag) 说，她的朋友鼓励她在离婚后举办派对。在他们的坚持下，她在一家酒吧楼上预订了一间不错的房间，她说那里有吵闹的音乐和“一些舞蹈，但还不够，因为人确实不够多。”</p><p> “为了好玩，压力很大，”她说。 “后来，我觉得我应该让自己感到非常沮丧，然后慢慢走出困境。”</p><p>旅游博主玛雅·普罗斯霍尔特 (Maja Proescholdt) 表示，她的离婚程序在没有律师的情况下完成，时间足够长，当文书工作完成时，她的大部分悲伤已经平复，她已经准备好参加派对了。</p><p>她的姐姐提供了一顶王冠和一条“最终离婚”的腰带。乐队出去跳舞，俱乐部的 DJ 喊道：“让我们为 Maja 的离婚派对举办吧！”</p><p> “那对我来说是人生的巅峰时刻，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Lane Florsheim： <a href="mailto:lane.florsheim@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">lane.florsheim@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9<author><![CDATA[Lane Florsheim]]></author><category>阿赫德</category><category>世界时尚</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>结婚/离婚</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>婚姻</category><category>离婚</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Europeans Are Becoming Poorer. ‘Yes, We’re All Worse Off.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>重视空闲时间的人口老龄化为经济停滞奠定了基础。然后是 Covid-19 和俄罗斯在乌克兰的战争。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817790/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="巴黎的一家餐厅。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>巴黎的一家餐厅。西里尔·马西尔哈西/彭博新闻<span>西里尔·马西尔哈西/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-fairless" itemprop="url" rel="author">汤姆·费尔莱斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日上午 12:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>欧洲人正面临着几十年来从未经历过的新经济现实。他们变得越来越穷。</p><p>随着欧洲人的购买力逐渐消失，长期以来因其<em>生活艺术而</em>被外人羡慕的大陆上的生活正在迅速失去光彩。</p><p>法国人正在少吃鹅肝，少喝红酒。西班牙人对橄榄油很吝啬。芬兰人被敦促在大风天使用桑拿浴室，因为那时能源价格较低。在整个德国，肉类和牛奶的消费量已降至三十年来的最低水平，一度繁荣的有机食品市场也陷入了低迷。意大利经济发展部长阿道夫·乌尔索（Adolfo Urso）于五月召开了一次危机会议，讨论该国最受欢迎的主食意大利面的价格，此前意大利面的价格上涨了全国通胀率的两倍多。</p><p>随着消费支出直线下降，欧洲在年初陷入衰退，强化了本世纪初开始出现的经济、政治和军事相对衰退的感觉。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="960" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818002?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>欧洲当前的困境由来已久。人口老龄化导致人们对空闲时间和工作保障的重视超过了收入，导致经济和生产力增长多年来一直乏善可陈。然后是Covid-19大流行和俄罗斯在乌克兰的旷日持久的战争的一对二重击。这场危机颠覆了全球供应链，导致能源和食品价格飙升，加剧了数十年来持续恶化的疾病。</p><p>政府的反应只会让问题更加复杂化。为了保住就业机会，他们主要向雇主提供补贴，导致消费者在价格冲击来临时没有现金缓冲。相比之下，美国人受益于廉价的能源和主要针对公民以保持消费的政府援助。</p><p>过去，非洲大陆强大的出口工业可能会起到拯救作用。但作为欧洲的重要市场，中国的缓慢复苏正在削弱这一增长支柱。高能源成本和自 20 世纪 70 年代以来从未见过的严重通货膨胀正在削弱制造商在国际市场上的价格优势，并破坏非洲大陆曾经和谐的劳资关系。随着全球贸易降温，欧洲对出口的严重依赖（出口占欧元区 GDP 的 50% 左右，而美国仅占 10%）正在成为一个弱点。</p><p>根据经济合作与发展组织（总部位于巴黎、主要由富裕国家组成的俱乐部）的数据，自 2019 年底以来，经过通货膨胀调整后，欧元区 20 国的私人消费下降了约 1%。在美国，劳动力市场强劲且收入不断增加，家庭收入增长了近9%。欧盟目前约占全球消费支出的 18%，而美国这一比例为 28%。十五年前，欧盟和美国各占总数的约四分之一。</p><p>根据通货膨胀和购买力进行调整后，德国的工资自 2019 年以来下降了约 3%，意大利和西班牙下降了 3.5%，希腊下降了 6%。根据经合组织的数据，同期美国的实际工资增长了约 6%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817793?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名老妇人离开柏林教堂的食品分发中心。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马库斯·施赖伯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这种痛苦波及到了中产阶级。 In Brussels, one of Europe&#39;s richest cities, teachers and nurses stood in line on a recent evening to collect half-price groceries from the back of a truck. The vendor, Happy Hours Market, collects food close to its expiration date from supermarkets and advertises it through an app. Customers can order in the early afternoon and collect their cut-price groceries in the evening.</p><p> “Some customers tell me, because of you I can eat meat two or three times per week,” said Pierre van Hede, who was handing out crates of groceries.</p><p> Karim Bouazza, a 33-year-old nurse who was stocking up on half-price meat and fish for his wife and two children, complained that inflation means “you almost need to work a second job to pay for everything.”</p><p> Similar services have sprung up across the region, marketing themselves as a way to reduce food waste as well as save money. TooGoodToGo, a company founded in Denmark in 2015 that sells leftover food from retailers and restaurants, has 76 million registered users across Europe, roughly three times the number at the end of 2020. In Germany, Sirplus, a startup created in 2017, offers “rescued” food, including products past their sell-by date, on its online store. So does Motatos, created in Sweden in 2014 and now present in Finland, Germany, Denmark and the UK</p><p> Spending on high-end groceries has collapsed. Germans consumed 52 kilograms of meat per person in 2022, about 8% less than the previous year and the lowest level since calculations began in 1989. While some of that reflects societal concerns about healthy eating and animal welfare, experts say the trend has been accelerated by meat prices which increased by up to 30% in recent months. Germans are also swapping meats such as beef and veal for less-expensive ones such as poultry, according to the Federal Information Center for Agriculture.</p><p> Thomas Wolff, an organic-food supplier near Frankfurt, said his sales fell by up to 30% last year as inflation surged. Wolff said he had hired 33 people earlier in the pandemic to handle strong demand for pricey ecological foodstuffs, but he has since let them all go.</p><p> Ronja Ebeling, a 26-year-old consultant and author based in Hamburg, said she saves about one-quarter of her income, partly because she worries about having enough money for retirement. She spends little on clothes or makeup and shares a car with her partner&#39;s father. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817996?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Weak spending and poor demographic prospects are making Europe less attractive for businesses ranging from consumer-goods giant <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/PG">Procter &amp; Gamble</a> to luxury empire <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/MC.FR">LVMH</a> <span>,</span> which are making an ever-larger share of their sales in North America.</p><p> “The US consumer is more resilient than in Europe,” <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/ULVR.LN">Unilever</a> <span>&#39;s</span></p> chief financial officer, Graeme Pitkethly, said in April.<p></p><p> The eurozone economy grew about 6% over the past 15 years, measured in dollars, compared with 82% for the US, according to International Monetary Fund data. That has left the average EU country poorer per head than every US state except Idaho and Mississippi, according to a report this month by the European Centre for International Political Economy, a Brussels-based independent think tank. If the current trend continues, by 2035 the gap between economic output per capita in the US and EU will be as large as that between Japan and Ecuador today, the report said.</p><p> On the Mediterranean island of Mallorca, businesses are lobbying for more flights to the US to increase the number of free-spending American tourists, said Maria Frontera, president of the Mallorca Chamber of Commerce&#39;s tourism commission. Americans spend about €260 ($292) per day on average on hotels compared with less than €180 ($202) for Europeans.</p><p> “This year we have seen a big change in the behavior of Europeans because of the economic situation we are dealing with,” said Frontera, who recently traveled to Miami to learn how to better cater to American customers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="789" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817781?width=1260&amp;height=789" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> People enjoy the warm temperatures in a beach bar in the seaside resort of S&#39;Arenal on Mallorca.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Clara Margais/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Weak growth and rising interest rates are straining Europe&#39;s generous welfare states, which provide popular healthcare services and pensions. European governments find the old recipes for fixing the problem are either becoming unaffordable or have stopped working. Three-quarters of a trillion euros in subsidies, tax breaks and other forms of relief have gone to consumers and businesses to offset higher energy costs—something economists say is now itself fueling inflation, defeating the subsidies&#39; purpose.</p><p> Public-spending cuts after the global financial crisis starved Europe&#39;s state-funded healthcare systems, especially the UK&#39;s National Health Service.</p><p> Vivek Trivedi, a 31-year-old anesthesiologist living in Manchester, England, earns about £51,000 ($67,000) per year for a 48-hour workweek. Inflation, which has been about 10% or higher in the UK for nearly a year, is devouring his monthly budget, he says. Trivedi said he shops for groceries in discount retailers and spends less on meals out. Some colleagues turned off their heating entirely over recent months, worried they wouldn&#39;t be able to afford sharply higher costs, he said.</p><p> Noa Cohen, a 28-year old public-affairs specialist in London, says she could quadruple her salary in the same job by leveraging her US passport to move across the Atlantic. Cohen recently got a 10% pay raise after switching jobs, but the increase was completely swallowed by inflation. She says friends are freezing their eggs because they can&#39;t afford children anytime soon, in the hope that they have enough money in future.</p><p> “It feels like a perma-freeze in living standards,” she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818000?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Huw Pill, the Bank of England&#39;s chief economist, warned UK citizens in April that they need to accept that they are poorer and stop pushing for higher wages. “Yes, we&#39;re all worse off,” he said, saying that seeking to offset rising prices with higher wages would only fuel more inflation.</p><p> With European governments needing to increase defense spending and given rising borrowing costs, economists expect taxes to increase, adding pressure on consumers. Taxes in Europe are already high relative to those in other wealthy countries, equivalent to around 40-45% of GDP compared with 27% in the US American workers take home almost three-quarters of their paychecks, including income taxes and Social Security taxes, while French and German workers keep just half.</p><p> The pauperization of Europe has bolstered the ranks of labor unions, which are picking up tens of thousands of members across the continent, reversing a decadeslong decline. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817780?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Bank of England has been raising interest rates to combat inflation.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jason Alden/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Higher unionization may not translate into fuller pockets for members. That&#39;s because many are pushing workers&#39; preference for more free time over higher pay, even in a world of spiraling skills shortages.</p><p> IG Metall, Germany&#39;s biggest trade union, is calling for a four-day work week at current salary levels rather than a pay raise for the country&#39;s metalworkers ahead of collective bargaining negotiations this November. Officials say the shorter week would improve workers&#39; health and quality of life while at the same time making the industry more attractive to younger workers.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What is your outlook for the economic health of Europe?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Almost half of employees in Germany&#39;s health industry choose to work around 30 hours per week rather than full time, reflecting tough working conditions, said Frank Werneke, chairman of the country&#39;s United Services Trade Union, which has added about 110,000 new members in recent months, the biggest increase in 22 years.</p><p> Kristian Kallio, a games developer in northern Finland, recently decided to reduce his working week by one-fifth to 30 hours in exchange for a 10% pay cut. He now makes about €2,500 per month. “Who wouldn&#39;t want to work shorter hours?” Kallio said. About one-third of his colleagues took the same deal, although leaders work full-time, said Kallio&#39;s boss, Jaakko Kylmäoja.</p><p> Kallio now works from 10 am to 4.30 pm He uses his extra free time for hobbies, to make good food and take long bike rides. “I don&#39;t see a reality where I would go back to normal working hours,” he said.</p><p> Igor Chaykovskiy, a 34-year-old IT worker in Paris, joined a trade union earlier this year to press for better pay and conditions. He recently received a 3.5% pay increase, about half the level of inflation. He thinks the union will give workers greater leverage to press managers. Still, it isn&#39;t just about pay. “Maybe they say you don&#39;t have an increase in salary, you have free sports lessons or music lessons,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="837" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817792?width=1260&amp;height=837" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mathias Senn, right, a butcher in Germany&#39;s wealthy Black Forest region, couldn&#39;t find local applicants to replace four workers who are preparing to retire, so he hired an apprentice from India, Rajakumar Bheemappa Lamani.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dominic Nahr for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At the <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/STLAM.MI">Stellantis</a> auto factory in Melfi, southern Italy, employees have worked shorter hours for years recently due to the difficulty of procuring raw materials and high energy costs, said Marco Lomio, a trade unionist with the Italian Union of Metalworkers. Hours worked have recently been reduced by around 30% and wages decreased proportionally.</p><p> “Between high inflation and rising energy costs for workers,” said Lomio, “it is difficult to bear all family expenses.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629<author><![CDATA[Tom Fairless]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Novel Coronaviruses</category><category> Infectious Diseases</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>outbreaks</category><category> epidemics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>novel coronaviruses</category><category> infectious diseases</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Germany in the World’ Review: Reichs, From First to Third]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The young nation-state of Germany turned to fascism and genocide in the 1930s. Yet before 1914 it was as liberal as France or Britain. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080563906716420"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818059?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Brandenburg Gate in Berlin at the end of the 19th century.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy Stock Photo </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080563906716420"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Josef Joffe</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 16, 2023 4:52 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Five hundred years ago, the land we now call Germany existed as the “Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation.” It wasn&#39;t a real empire and certainly wasn&#39;t holy or Roman or even particularly German. It was rather a hodgepodge of fiefdoms, creeds and nationalities. Napoleon put an end to this “empire” in 1806.</p><p> Modern Germany, a babe among the classic nation-states, was born in 1871, when Prussia pounded together 25 little Germanys. Unification triggered growth, then ambition, then two horrifying world wars. Amputation cut the behemoth down to size. Reunified today, Germany is Europe&#39;s largest economy and an admired citizen of the world.</p><p> Yet there are continuities, which is the main theme of David Blackbourn&#39;s “Germany in the World: A Global History, 1500-2000.” These continuities, though, aren&#39;t of the facile character-as-destiny sort—from Luther to Hitler, as a 1941 tome had it. Mr. Blackbourn bids us to look through a “wider lens,” which reveals that Germany was not Europe&#39;s odd-man-out.</p><p> Take German nationalism. He reminds us that the “1860s were a pivotal decade” in the annals of nationalism. Invented by Revolutionary France, the ideology gripped all new nation-states: Germany, Italy and Japan. America, too, went on a nationalist binge in the 1890s. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/7b3bf44f-b8db-410c-9d26-8805a032d050.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The Kaiser&#39;s Germany was not on a <em>Sonderweg</em> , a separate poisoned path. Nor was the Reich before 1914 less liberal than France or Britain by the standards of the time. Germany was beholden to the rule of law and boasted a strong parliament and a vigorous press. Why did its regime turn to genocide? In spite of the growing literature on the Holocaust, the cosmic riddle remains unsolved.</p><p> Mr. Blackbourn counsels that “we should challenge the persistent idea that landlocked Germany was wrapped up in its own affairs”—an unto-itself—“while others transformed relations between Europe and the non-European world.” In fact, he contends, the “Holy Roman Empire was a world in motion.” Over the next 150 pages, he recounts how Germany&#39;s sailors manned the ships of the seafaring nations, its soldiers served in the British and Dutch empires, and its restless inhabitants struck out from Eastern Europe to the Western Hemisphere.</p><p> Even so, the global wanderlust of German sailors, savants and settlers doesn&#39;t quite compare to what the real globalizers did, conquering and peopling the four corners of the earth. Diaspora isn&#39;t empire, never mind how many millions of Germans settled in the United States; and anyway the few possessions Germany grabbed were lost in the 1919 Versailles settlement. The defeated Germans should thank the victors who spared them countless wars against the locals, which drained the blood and wealth of the colonial powers after World War II.</p><p> The German (or German-speaking) “empire” was a lot cheaper. It was a cultural dominion. We can&#39;t think about modernity without Goethe and Schiller, Bach and Beethoven, Marx and Hegel, Kant and Wittgenstein, Rilke and Mann, Freud and Jung, Einstein, Planck and Heisenberg. Germans like GW Pabst and Fritz Lang wrote the first chapters of the cinematic canon. Carl Laemmle invented Hollywood.</p><p> Mr. Blackbourn reminds us that American higher education was “remade” in the image of the “German model.” Harvard, Stanford and Johns Hopkins (“Göttingen in Baltimore”) adopted the German concept of the research university. Later they profited from a tragic windfall gain, when thousands of German academics found refuge in the US—Hitler&#39;s “gift.”</p><p> Curiously missing from a section of the book titled “The Triumph of German Culture,” spanning the 60 years between Bismarck and Hitler, is the momentous Jewish role. Something like 39 Jewish Nobel laureates hailed from Germany and Austria during this period, and more from the rest of <em>Mitteleuropa</em> . And then there were the writers of fiction, like Franz Kafka, and composers, like Arnold Schoenberg, who broke the mold.</p><p> Mr. Blackbourn&#39;s commendable passion for evenhandedness sometimes gets the better of him. Thus he depicts the boundless slaughter after the Final Solution was formulated in 1942 as, though “German-directed,” a “pan-European operation” by peoples under the German knout, especially in Eastern Europe. This complicity doesn&#39;t obliterate the difference between rider and horse. Nazi Germany designed the project and built the death factories. Some Poles, Ukrainians et al. were willing collaborators. But they were not masters.</p><p> We get a similar whiff of “yes, but” in Mr. Blackbourn&#39;s account of the two world wars. Yes, unrestricted U-boat warfare brought the US into the first, but German civilians suffered under the blockade. And, yes, in the second, German war-making was indiscriminately cruel, but area bombing inflicted terrible misery on German innocents.</p><p> How, other than loss and devastation, did Germany go so fast from fascist dictatorship to peaceable republic? The US solved postwar Germany&#39;s security dilemma by extending its nuclear umbrella. Safety breeds good things: prosperity, democracy and self-containment. The rest of Europe no longer fears the nation that is again No. 1.</p><p> So is the “German Problem” a thing of the past? Not quite. Twelve years ago, as Mr. Blackbourn points out, Poland&#39;s foreign minister remarked that he feared German power less than German inactivity. Sometimes lessons are too well learned. Passivity no longer works as a grand strategy, as Russia made clear when it invaded Ukraine last year and forced Germany to lend its might to the victim.</p><p> Too much of a good thing might also hold for “Germany in the World,” which runs close to 800 pages. The research is magnificent, with 80 pages of endnotes. But the central idea—Germany as a Western nation like the others—is often submerged beneath a torrent of names, details and digressions. That said, the book is superbly written, and even Germany buffs will find a surfeit of riches.</p><p> <em>Mr. Joffe teaches at the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>战争罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>战争罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[High-Earning Retirement Savers Are Losing Some of Their 401(k) Tax Break]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Catch-up contributions will have to be done after taxes for those who make more than $145,000 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816650/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> PHOTO ILLUSTRATION BY ELENA SCOTTI/THE WALL STREET JOURNAL, ISTOCK (3), PIXELSQUID <span>PHOTO ILLUSTRATION BY ELENA SCOTTI/THE WALL STREET JOURNAL, ISTOCK (3), PIXELSQUID</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001052376"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001052376"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Anne Tergesen</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 16, 2023 10:47 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-breaks-401k-contributions-2868ffdc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Millions of high-earning Americans are slated to lose a popular tax deduction starting next year.</p><p> Savers ages 50 and older can make catch-up contributions in their 401(k) accounts each year, with eligible workers allowed to put an extra $7,500 into their accounts, for a total of $30,000, this year.</p><p> Starting next year, those catch-up funds will be funneled only into after-tax Roth accounts for those who earned more than $145,000 the previous year. The change is part of a set of new rules <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/401k-changes-retirement-plans-congress-11671482120?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Congress passed in December</a> . In 2022, 16% of eligible participants took advantage of catch-ups, according to Vanguard Group.</p><p> This change means many workers will pay taxes on their catch-up money up front during high-earning years, rather than in retirement when they may be in a lower tax bracket. It stands to reshape how many Americans save for retirement and create financial and estate-planning strategies.</p><p> Making catch-up contributions with pretax money has been a boon for high earners. For example, someone in a 35% bracket would receive a $2,625 tax deduction for a $7,500 catch-up contribution, while someone in the 22% bracket would deduct $1,650.</p><p> While some Americans will pay more in taxes under the new rules, financial advisers say there will be a benefit to getting near-retirees to put more money into a Roth, where money grows and can be withdrawn tax-free. The changes don&#39;t apply to IRAs, which allow a catch-up contribution in 2023 of $1,000 for savers 50 and over on top of the $6,500 annual limit.</p><p> “The Roth is such a powerful savings tool that I try to have at least some dollars going into that bucket for all my clients, regardless of tax bracket,” said Cristina Guglielmetti, a financial adviser in Brooklyn, NY</p><h3> Benefits of Roth</h3><p> Retirees with nest eggs in traditional accounts must pay ordinary income tax when they withdraw the money. In Roth accounts, workers can build a pot of tax-free money to spend in years in which tapping other accounts would push them into a higher tax bracket or force them to pay higher Medicare premiums.</p><p> Many assume they will be in a lower tax bracket in retirement, but that isn&#39;t always the case, said Ed Slott,</p> an adviser who specializes in retirement accounts.<p></p><p> Because high earners often amass large balances in traditional 401(k)s and individual retirement accounts, many find themselves in the same or a higher tax bracket when the Internal Revenue Service requires them to start pulling money out of those accounts at age 73.</p><p> The new requirement for catch-up contributions is a “gift to high earners” who might otherwise overlook the benefits of tax-free growth, he said.</p><p> Because Roths grow tax-free, they are better options for big savers than taxable brokerage accounts, which require owners to pay taxes annually on dividends, interest and realized capital gains, advisers say. Roths also have big advantages for heirs, who receive tax-free income.</p><p> Both Roth and traditional accounts must be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/irs-changes-guidelines-for-inherited-iras-causing-confusion-and-pushback-11659309278?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">liquidated over 10 years</a> by most nonspouse beneficiaries.</p><h3> Companies call for a delay</h3><p> Though the change is set to kick in Jan. 1, some companies and plan providers say they need more time to meet the logistical challenges of identifying who earned more than $145,000 the previous year and retooling payroll and other systems to ensure their catch-ups go into a Roth.</p><p> More than 200 employers, 401(k) record-keepers, and payroll providers recently sent a letter to Congress requesting a two-year delay. Signed by companies including Delta Air Lines, Anheuser-Busch, and Fidelity Investments, which administers 24,800 corporate retirement accounts for employers, the letter says many won&#39;t be able to change their systems in time to meet the deadline.</p><p> “For many of these plans, unless this requirement is delayed…their only means of compliance will be to eliminate all catch-up contributions for 2024,” the letter said.</p><p> Sharon Lukacs,</p> executive director of the New York State Deferred Compensation Board, said the state&#39;s $31 billion deferred compensation plan allows the 2,236 local employers using the plan to decide whether to offer a Roth. Currently, 1,200 have opted against doing so, in some cases because their payroll systems couldn&#39;t handle Roth contributions.<p></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Does a Roth makes sense for 401(k) catch-up contributions?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> So far, 150 of the 1,200 have agreed to add a Roth by Jan. 1, she said.</p><p> Currently, 30% of Fidelity&#39;s 24,800 401(k) clients lack a Roth feature, said Dave Gray, head of workplace retirement offerings and platforms at the Boston-based company. Unless those employers adopt a Roth option before the new law goes into effect, they will have to eliminate catch-up contributions for all of their workers, Gray said.</p><p> Payroll providers, employers and 401(k) record-keepers are working to meet the deadline, but are waiting for guidance from regulators on questions including whether they must seek permission from high earners to put their catch-up contributions into a Roth or can do so automatically, Gray said. If the guidance comes late in the year, companies might not have enough time to adjust their systems, he said.</p><p> Some retirement savings plans, including those for state employees in South Dakota and Idaho, can&#39;t add a Roth unless their state legislatures pass laws, said Matthew Petersen, executive director of the National Association of Government Defined Contribution Administrators, which has 250 members. Some employers must negotiate with unions to add a Roth, he said.</p><p> A spokesperson for the Treasury Department said it plans to issue guidance in the near future but declined to comment on the request for a delay.</p><h3> A fix from Congress</h3><p> Another question hanging over catch-up contributions resulted from a drafting error in the retirement bill that Congress passed late last year, which many lawyers specializing in retirement plans interpret as prohibiting catch-up contributions for all workers starting in 2024.</p><p> In a May 23 letter to the Treasury Department and IRS, lawmakers including Sen. Mike Crapo (R., Idaho) and Rep. Richard Neal (D., Mass.) said Congress intends to “introduce technical corrections legislation” to fix that problem.</p><p> “Congress did not intend to disallow catch-up contributions,” the letter said.</p><p> Write to Anne Tergesen at <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2d22c5e9-a490-4c14-9b85-792395763a6e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 14:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-breaks-401k-contributions-2868ffdc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-breaks-401k-contributions-2868ffdc<author><![CDATA[Anne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Individual Retirement Accounts</category><category>个人财务</category><category>Retirement Planning</category><category> Tax Strategies</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>individual retirement accounts</category><category>个人财务</category><category>retirement planning</category><category> tax strategies </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The New Workday Dead Zone When Nothing Gets Done]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Late afternoon, when many colleagues vanish, is why so many managers hate hybrid work <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816492/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Blake Cale for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2) <span>Photo Illustration by Blake Cale for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001051789"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001051789"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-498821" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers" itemprop="url" rel="author">Callum Borchers</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>下午 4 点的会议被取消，因为一半的团队成员无法参加。您发送一封电子邮件，其中包含主要讨论点，回复从晚上一直持续到第二天早上。本来可以在晚餐前达成的共识现在却在第二天形成。</p><p>传统的下班时间已经成为许多公司的死区，但员工们并不仅仅是为了放松一下一天的工作。工人们表示，他们利用下午 4 点至 6 点的弹性工作时间轮流带孩子拼车、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-working-out-during-the-workday-is-the-ultimate-power-move-11672863482?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去健身房</a>或避开交通拥堵，通常需要在晚上第三班才能完成当天的任务。当领导者认为他们没有投入八个小时或更多小时的工作时，他们会感到不满，并且不愿意放弃制定自己时间表的自由。</p><p>尽管磨牙的通勤和昂贵的午餐又回来了，但许多员工仍然坚持着新冠病毒时代早下班、晚补班的习惯。斯坦福大学的一项<a href="https://nbloom.people.stanford.edu/sites/g/files/sbiybj24291/files/media/file/golfingfromhome.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">研究</a>表明，工作日下午 4 点，高尔夫球场就挤满了人，纽约市的许多餐馆也是如此。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>研究人员记录了他们所谓的“<a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/worklab/triple-peak-day" target="_blank" class="icon none">三重高峰</a>”现象，即员工的键盘活动在早上和下午激增，然后在晚上 10 点左右出现第三次。科技巨头预测这种模式将持续下去。</p><p>在最近的一个月 Microsoft Teams 软件使用情况样本中，安排在下午 4 点至 6 点之间进行的虚拟会议和面对面会议的比例较去年同期下降了 7%，尽管办公室返工现象普遍存在。</p><p>老板可以把员工拖回办公桌前，但如果你能把他们留在那里直到朝九晚五的工作日结束或更长时间，那就祝你好运了。下午 4 点至 6 点的死区是许多高管对混合工作感到暴躁的原因之一。他们说，这是联系人员最困难的时期，如果每个人都在场并亲自负责，事情会更容易，尽管许多员工似乎也提前离开办公室。</p><p><strong>灵活性的代价</strong></p><p>可替代的时间对于那些进行可替代的人来说非常有用。对于经理和同事来说，一个人的休息可能会让另一个人头疼。</p><p>多元化培训软件制造商 Kanarys 的产品营销副总裁阿尔伯特·方 (Albert Fong) 表示：“许多公司都采取了宽松的做法，因为他们相信我们都是成年人，因此每个人都会自律，并且无论在什么时候工作都保持积极性。” “那不是真的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="622" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816891?width=639&amp;height=622" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Kanarys 产品营销副总裁 Albert Fong 表示，灵活性可能是一个陷阱，会助长我们永远在线的工作文化。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：方伟强</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Fong 补充道，灵活性可能是一个陷阱，会助长我们永远在线的工作文化。他经常发现自己整个晚上都在刷新手机收件箱，或者在周日打开笔记本电脑，以查看随时工作的同事发来的消息，而不是在下午晚些时候的聚会中精力充沛地完成一天的工作。</p><p>微软未来工作计划总经理 Colette Stallbaumer 总结道：“我们如何才能让我的灵活性不再成为你的挑战？”</p><p>麦肯锡公司副合伙人安娜·保拉·卡尔沃 (Ana Paula Calvo) 表示，她考虑改变自己的工作时间会对他人产生怎样的影响。她有时会在晚上或周末工作，以弥补许多工作日下午 5:30 去托儿所的时间。在任何新项目开始时，她都会召开规范制定会议，让她的团队知道他们没有加班的压力。</p><p> “人们知道，如果我在晚上 11 点回复他们，并不意味着我希望他们立即回复，”她说。</p><p><strong>它可以等待——或者也许不能</strong></p><p>几位企业领导人告诉我，为了招募和留住顶尖人才，有必要满足员工的个人约会——欢乐时光瑜伽、青少年大号课程。他们补充说，不过，这肯定会让会议达到法定人数变得困难。其他人，尤其是没有孩子的工人，则抱怨说，自从人们普遍接受在正常工作时间休息以来，他们的工作日变得更长且更难以预测。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>下午 4 点至 6 点，您和您的同事在做什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>俄勒冈州的制药运营总监玛丽亚·巴纳赫 (Maria Banach) 表示，有时她想召集小组来解决问题，结果却发现团队中有人已经离线了几个小时。这看起来似乎不是很长，但她的同事分布在多个时区，重叠的工作时间也很有限。巴纳赫说，如果一两个人提早离开，问题可能会持续一夜，但每一天都很宝贵。她公司生产的药品在生产后17天就过期了。</p><p> “安排会议变得很困难，但我学会了：在早上进行，而不是在周五，”她说。</p><p>一些高管已经接受、甚至欣然接受这样一个现实：下午 4 点到 6 点之间几乎没有什么事情可做。 安东尼·斯蒂芬 (Anthony Stephan)</p> chief learning officer of Deloitte US, says recorded tutorials are now a centerpiece of the firm&#39;s professional-development program. Getting employees together for an end-of-the-day training session is seldom an option any more, he says. They hone new skills when they feel like it.<p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="852" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815827?width=639&amp;height=852" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mercedes Aycinena, CEO of Komet USA, usually leaves the office at 5 pm to spend time with her children and then resumes work later if needed.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mercedes Aycinena</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>斯蒂芬是五个孩子的父亲，他在下午 5 点强迫自己停下来。他最初担心其他人会在他下班后继续忙碌，但现在他意识到其他人正在提前或准时结束。对于紧急情况，他告诉他的团队在电子邮件主题行中添加#riticnow。他认为，大多数事情都可以等到第二天早上 5 点 15 分锻炼之后再做。</p><p>在位于南卡罗来纳州的牙科设备制造商 Komet USA，下午 4 点之后或周五下午开会违反公司政策，特殊情况除外。去年晋升为最高职位的首席执行官梅赛德斯·艾辛纳(Mercedes Aycinena)在对员工进行民意调查后于去年秋天介绍了这些日历块。</p><p> Aycinena 拥有约 100 名员工，她通常在下午 5 点离开办公室，与她的三个孩子共度时光，然后根据需要稍后再继续工作。她还允许下属调整工作时间，并认为灵活性有助于将过去一年的人员流动率从 50% 降低到 15%。</p><p> “我讨厌四点之后的会议，”她说。 “我的大脑已经完成了。”</p><p>写信给Callum Borchers： <a href="mailto:callum.borchers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">callum.borchers@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/12865c40-068f-4100-aa18-f73fd5f66fae.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0<author><![CDATA[Callum Borchers]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Work-Life Balance</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Telecommuting</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>work-life balance</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>telecommuting</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Arts Calendar for the Week of July 16]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> 《芭比娃娃》和《奥本海默》终于上映，一部讲述自由潜水极限运动的令人痛心的纪录片，英伦流行偶像 Blur 回归等等。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022672"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817403?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ryan Gosling and Margot Robbie</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：华纳兄弟。</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022672"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> 《华尔街日报》艺术评论人员</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 5:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-16-airdigital-8919e68"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><h3>电影</h3><p><strong>《芭比》</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：芭比女孩终于在夏季最受期待的电影之一中邀请观众进入她的芭比世界。 Margot Robbie plays the iconic <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MAT" class="company-name">Mattel</a> creation with Ryan Gosling as her Ken in a film with more stars than rooms in a Malibu Dreamhouse.亚美莉卡·费雷拉、蕾亚·帕尔曼、凯特·麦金农、伊萨·雷、杜阿·利帕、刘思慕、约翰·塞纳、海伦·米伦、迈克尔·塞拉等人在格蕾塔·葛韦格执导的电影中扮演了角色，该电影由她与诺亚·鲍姆巴赫共同编剧。</p><p> <strong>《奥本海默》</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：夏季电影的另一场震撼人心的电影，克里斯托弗·诺兰这部备受期待的传记片讲述了一位帮助研制原子弹的理论物理学家，主演希里安·墨菲，其他好莱坞熟人如艾米莉·布朗特、马特·达蒙、小罗伯特·唐尼、弗洛伦斯·皮尤、拉米·马雷克和肯尼思·布拉纳。</p><p> <strong>《蜘蛛网》</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：如果巴本海默的炒作没有让你兴奋，本周恐怖片粉丝还有其他选择，包括这个故事：一个 8 岁的孩子试图揭开他父母一直向他隐瞒的关于他家的邪恶秘密。塞缪尔·博丁 (Samuel Bodin) 执导克里斯·托马斯·德夫林 (Chris Thomas Devlin)（2022 年的《德州电锯杀人狂》），塞斯·罗根 (Seth Rogen) 和埃文·戈德堡 (Evan Goldberg) 担任制片人。</p><p> <strong>“豆豆泡泡”</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：玩具们在影院度过了重要的一周；这款产品友好型产品着眼于 Beanie Babies 的病毒式成功。扎克·加利凡纳基斯饰演泰·华纳，他是制作可爱小动物的公司的创始人，其他演员还有伊丽莎白·班克斯、莎拉·斯努克和杰拉尔丁·维斯瓦纳坦。克里斯汀·戈尔 (Kristin Gore) 和达米安·库拉什 (Damian Kulash) 执导的喜剧片在 Apple TV+ 上进行了有限的院线放映。</p><p> <strong>《恐惧之夜》</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：电影制片人、剧作家兼演员尼尔·拉布特 (Neil LaBute) 担任导演，执导了这部动作惊悚片，讲述一名伊拉克战争老兵（Maggie Q 饰演）利用自己所受的训练，对抗一群扰乱她姐姐单身派对的家庭入侵者的故事。</p><h3>电视</h3><p><strong>“南方故事讲述者”</strong> <em>（PBS，7 月 18 日）</em> ：克雷格·雷诺的三集迷你剧是一封写给美国南方和那里蓬勃发展的创造力的情书。雷诺先生对音乐家、作家、电影制片人等进行了剖析，不仅探讨了创作过程，还探讨了引导这些艺术家走上当前道路的独特历史和环境。采访对象包括小说家安吉·托马斯、音乐家莱尔·洛维特、杰森·伊斯贝尔和阿曼达·夏尔斯、演员比利·鲍勃·松顿和烹饪历史学家迈克尔·特威蒂。</p><p> <strong>《歌利亚》</strong> <em>（Showtime，7 月 16 日）</em> ：罗布·福特和克里斯托弗·狄龙在 Showtime 上执导了一部由三部分组成的纪录片系列，探讨篮球传奇人物威尔特·张伯伦的遗产和性格。我们的电视评论家<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/goliath-review-how-wilt-chamberlain-changed-the-game-518350d4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指出</a>，“《歌利亚》中出现的有血有肉的人类坦诚得令人耳目一新，信息丰富且讨人喜欢。”</p><p> <strong>《火线警探：原始城市》</strong> <em>（FX，7 月 18 日）</em> ：这部荣获艾美奖的犯罪剧的续集即将上映，蒂莫西·奥利芬特将回归饰演美国元帅雷兰·吉文斯。和上一剧一样，这部迷你剧借鉴了埃尔莫·伦纳德的作品——这次是他的小说《原始城市：底特律的正午》——来渲染它的新西方故事。</p><p> <strong>《最深的呼吸》</strong> <em>（Netflix，7 月 19 日）</em> ：那些对海洋有恐惧的人应该避免观看劳拉·麦甘 (Laura McGann) 的关于自由潜水的纪录片，在这项运动中，人们试图在没有任何安全设备的情况下，一口气呼吸到尽可能深的深度。她跟随意大利冠军阿莱西娅·泽基尼 (Alessia Zecchini) 尝试创造纪录并在红海深处的水下隧道中航行。</p><p> <strong>《赞美皮蒂》</strong> <em>（Freeform，7 月 21 日）</em> ：在这部由安妮·墨菲、约翰·赵、史蒂芬·鲁特、克里斯汀·巴伦斯基和科尔西·克莱蒙斯配音的动画剧集中，一位纽约社交名流在她的父亲去世后，接管了他的小镇邪教，成为了一位另类的影响者。</p><p> <strong>“斯蒂芬·库里：被低估”</strong> <em>（Apple TV+，7 月 21 日）</em> ：虽然斯蒂芬·库里可能达不到乔丹或卡里姆的水平，但他仍然是“山羊”的热门话题，并且不可否认的是，他在三分线外的令人惊叹的表现永远改变了篮球比赛。彼得·尼克斯 (Peter Nicks) 的新纪录片讲述了这位超级巨星勇士如何走到今天的位置，从卑微的高中出身，到因身材问题而进入大学生涯，再到成为 NBA 冠军。</p><p> <strong>《他们克隆了蒂龙》</strong> <em>（Netflix，7 月 21 日）</em> ：在朱尔·泰勒这部由约翰·博耶加、泰柔娜·帕里斯、杰米·福克斯、大卫·艾伦·格里尔和基弗·萨瑟兰主演的科幻喜剧中，政府的基因阴谋出了差错。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817404?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿莱西娅·泽基尼《最深的呼吸》</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Netflix</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>剧院</h3><p><strong>《Here Lies Love》</strong> <em>（纽约百老汇剧院，7 月 20 日开幕）</em> ：Talking Heads 主唱大卫·伯恩 (David Byrne) 与百老汇联系在一起可能是一个奇怪的名字，尤其是在他的热门剧《美国乌托邦》之后。但是胖子苗条呢？ The two teamed with choreographer Annie-B Parson and director Alex Timbers on a musical whose topic itself is unconventional: the rise and fall of Filipino First Lady</p> Imelda Marcos.<p></p><h3>音乐</h3><p><strong>Blur，“达伦之歌”</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：英国摇滚乐队 Blur 带着他们近十年来的第一张专辑回归，他们与 Oasis 的竞争使英国流行音乐成为世界现象。该乐队与制作人詹姆斯·福特合作，推出了一张包含他们的经典声音和他们这一代人的关注点的唱片，同时也致力于成为当下的潮流。</p><p> <strong>Jaboukie，“所有听不见的人都必须感受”</strong> <em>（7 月 21 日）</em> ：演员、作家兼喜剧演员 Jaboukie Young-White 在他的简历中添加了另一行：唱片艺术家。他的第一张专辑讲述了移民孩子成长过程中的挣扎，并歌颂了他的性取向。</p><p> <strong>Nils Lofgren, “Mountains”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : Part of Bruce Springsteen&#39;s E Street Band and</p> Neil Young&#39;s Crazy Horse, the multi-instrumentalist&#39;s new solo LP includes features from Mr. Young, David Crosby (who died before the album was released) and Ringo Starr.<p></p><h3>舞蹈</h3><p><strong>“One Dance”</strong> <em>（大卫·H·科赫剧院，纽约，7 月 20 日至 22 日）</em> ：首尔大都会舞蹈剧院在这部由 Hyejin Jung 与 Sung Hoon Kim 和 Jae Duk Kim 共同编排的有限参与舞蹈中，对韩国传统舞蹈和音乐进行了现代演绎。</p><h3>歌剧</h3><p><strong>“Henri VIII”</strong> <em>(Fisher Center, Annandale-on-Hudson, July 21-30)</em> : Part of the Bard SummerScape festival, Camille Saint-Saëns&#39;s opera about the king&#39;s quest to divorce Catherine of Aragon to wed Anne Boleyn gets a new staging from Jean-Romain Vesperini. Alfred Walker sings the title role with Lindsay Ammann and Amanda Woodbury playing his ill-fated wives.</p><h3>艺术</h3><p><strong>“树与蛇：印度早期佛教艺术，公元前 200 年至公元 400 年”</strong> <em>（纽约大都会第五大道博物馆，7 月 21 日至 11 月 13 日）</em> ：展览讲述了佛教艺术的起源及其对该地区及其历史的不可避免的影响。超过 140 件物品追溯了从前宗教雕塑开始到世俗和精神思想和文物的国际交流的叙述。</p><p> <strong>“爱德华·霍珀与安角：照亮美国风景”</strong> <em>（马萨诸塞州格洛斯特安角博物馆，7 月 22 日至 10 月 16 日）</em> ：这场展览定于这位伟大的美国画家的生日当天开幕，展出了 60 多件作品，探讨了他访问安角并被其自然和人造美景所吸引时职业生涯中的一个关键点。 Also included are works by Josephine N. Hopper, his muse and wife, but also an accomplished painter.</p><p><strong>北部艺术周末</strong><em>（纽约多个地点，7 月 21 日至 24 日）</em> ：自 2020 年启动以来，哈德逊河谷和卡茨基尔地区艺术空间之间的这一年度合作已扩大到包括 130 多名参与者。其中包括 Magazzino Italian Art 等机构、Susan Eley Fine Art 等画廊、哈德逊谷莎士比亚节等表演场所、托马斯·科尔国家历史遗址等历史名胜等等。</p><h3>其他</h3><p><strong>《皮克敏 4》</strong> <em>（Nintendo Switch，7 月 21 日）</em> ：这款广受好评的解谜系列游戏，玩家集结一群名为皮克敏的长叶生物来克服挑战，自 2013 年以来的第一部作品再次回归。</p><h3>最后一次通话</h3><p><strong>“Peter Pan Goes Wrong”</strong> <em>(Barrymore Theatre, New York, closes July 23)</em> : From the creators of the hit comedy “The Play That Goes Wrong,” this production sees another group of devoted if less-than-capable theater folk trying to stage a show, this time the 1904 JM Barrie classic “Peter and Wendy.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —欲了解更多艺术日历列表，请访问 wsj.com。写信给 brian.kelly@wsj.com 和 julia.fischer@wsj.com。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-16-airdigital-8919e68</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-16-airdigital-8919e68<category>艺术评论</category><category>游戏</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>舞蹈/芭蕾舞</category><category>电子竞技</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>故事片</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电视/广播节目表</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>歌剧</category><category>运动的</category><category>剧院</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>活动日历</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>游戏</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>舞蹈</category><category>芭蕾舞</category><category>电子竞技</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>故事片</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电视</category><category>电台列表</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>歌剧</category><category>运动的</category><category>剧院</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>活动日历</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Watercolors Unboxed’ Review: Luminous, Liquid Visions]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>伍斯特艺术博物馆推出了一系列世界级的水彩画收藏品，这些水彩画作品因脆弱而很少见，作者包括温斯洛·霍默、约翰·辛格·萨金特、阿梅迪奥·莫迪利亚尼和雅各布·劳伦斯等艺术家。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590053711666675490"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="564" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817308?width=860&amp;height=564" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Muddy Alligators&#39; (1917) by John Singer Sargent</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590053711666675490"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">巴里摩尔·劳伦斯·谢勒</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 15, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/watercolors-unboxed-review-worcester-sargent-homer-modigliani-lawrence-7a2421b4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Worcester, Mass.</em></p><p> Think “art museum,” and big-city institutions like Washington&#39;s National Gallery, the Art Institute of Chicago and New York&#39;s Metropolitan first spring to mind. But the current “Watercolors Unboxed” show at the Worcester Art Museum in central Massachusetts makes you realize that regional museums throughout the US often harbor treasures that rank with those of the majors. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <em>Watercolors Unboxed</em></p><p> <strong>Worcester Art Museum, through Sept. 10</strong></p></div></div><p> Founded in 1896, the Worcester Art Museum not only boasts admirable collections of European and American painting and sculpture, superb mosaics, some 3,700 Japanese woodblock prints, and the famed John Woodman Higgins Armory Collection—it also houses a celebrated trove of watercolors, which because of their fragility and sensitivity to light are rarely displayed.</p><p> Through Sept. 10, WAM is presenting a choice selection of 40 European and American works created between the 1870s and 1950s representing a variety of artistic approaches to this subtle but challenging medium. Organized by Nancy Kathryn Burns, WAM&#39;s curator of prints, drawings and photographs, the show features rarely exhibited watercolors by such American luminaries as Childe Hassam, Winslow Homer, Rockwell Kent, John La Farge, John Singer Sargent and Andrew Wyeth (his riveting 1957 “The Rope,” a study for “Hay Ledge”). It also includes examples by artists less known for their activity in watercolor and gouache (also called “opaque watercolor”), notably Amedeo Modigliani, Gustave Baumann and Ernst Ludwig Kirchner. These newly unboxed paintings range stylistically from Sargent&#39;s bravura brushwork to the deliberate poster-like rawness of social commentator Jacob Lawrence&#39;s 1943 “They live In firetraps.” Also featured are examples from WAM&#39;s collection of watercolors painted or influenced by members of the San Ildefonso school, a collective of Native American artists working in the Southwest during the first half of the 20th century. Because most of these pieces have so long been safely archived, they are in prime condition, their fragile pigments fresh and unfaded. Moreover, beyond reflecting over 70 years&#39; progression of watercolor styles, they illustrate a variety of techniques employed by the artists to achieve their effects, some not always obvious to viewers. Informative technical discussions are included in the wall cards. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817310?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Yonkers From the Palisades&#39; (1916) by Childe Hassam</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For example, Childe Hassam&#39;s 1916 “Yonkers From the Palisades,” a panoramic view looking across the Hudson River from New Jersey&#39;s craggy shore, achieves textural contrast between the quick, fragmented brush strokes of the cliffs and their autumnal foliage and his flowing, idealized blue water. To paint the river, Hassam applied layers of blue and yellow-green wash, before tamping them down with a bit of sponge or other absorbent material.</p><p> Similarly, Rockwell Kent&#39;s 1926-27 “Boy on Cliff” demonstrates wash manipulated to create a different effect: Here, a lone youth, precariously balancing on a narrow rock outcropping, ponders the sea below. Kent surrounds the boy&#39;s head with a mystic aureole of light against the picture&#39;s glowing polychrome sky. As Ms. Burns observed to me, “he produced that sky by brushing adjacent washes of various hues, and most probably using a similar absorbent material to apply further layers of blue and rose tones.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817309?width=700&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Venice&#39; (1911) by Maurice Prendergast</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Art Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-curatorial-imagination-of-walter-hopps-review-seeing-like-a-visionary-70cec571?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Curatorial Imagination of Walter Hopps&#39; Review: Seeing Like a Visionary</a> <span class="date">July 8, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/frank-stewarts-nexus-an-american-photographers-journey-1960s-to-the-present-review-visual-music-22dda449?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Frank Stewart&#39;s Nexus: An American Photographer&#39;s Journey, 1960s to the Present&#39; Review: Visual Music</a> <span class="date">July 4, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/edvard-munch-trembling-earth-review-man-screams-nature-whispers-68da01ff?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Edvard Munch: Trembling Earth&#39; Review: Man Screams, Nature Whispers</a> <span class="date">July 1, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/young-picasso-in-paris-review-a-giant-comes-of-age-4ea04e4f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Young Picasso in Paris&#39; Review: A Giant Comes of Age</a> <span class="date">June 24, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Altogether different in mood, Maurice Prendergast&#39;s effervescent “Venice” (1911) exemplifies his well-known use of staccato dabs of color with which he recorded the view outside his Venetian hospital window while recuperating from emergency surgery during a painting holiday there. Characteristically, he makes the mosaic-like dabs scintillate by leaving surrounding areas of the cream paper visible.</p><p> Not surprisingly, Sargent and Homer are easily the show&#39;s stars. Sargent&#39;s “Muddy Alligators” (1917) is among his most exceptional watercolor essays, painted during a trip to Florida after he had essentially abandoned portraiture for the landscape painting that had long been his great love. Over graphite outlines, he loosely deploys quick patches of watercolor to capture a group of these fearsome reptiles lolling about their swampy habitat. Sargent pools some patches and scrapes away others—notably to form the sharp teeth of the open-mouthed gator in the foreground. Hanging alongside the painting, three of Sargent&#39;s detailed pencil sketches of alligators reveal the intensive preparatory study behind the artist&#39;s apparent spontaneity. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817307?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Rum Cay&#39; (1898-99) by Winslow Homer</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Created during Homer&#39;s second visit to the Bahamas, “Rum Cay” (1898-99) shows a muscular Bahamian running past a large sea turtle against a minimal beachscape comprising three spare horizontal bands of color wash. Apart from the oblique reference to Aesop&#39;s tortoise and hare, the runner bespeaks Homer&#39;s consummate skill at capturing the athletic human body in action, from the splendid delineation of the man&#39;s face and sunlit torso to the flexed toes of his left foot. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="901" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817361?width=639&amp;height=901" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Homer&#39;s &#39;Old Friends&#39; (1894)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In contrast, Homer&#39;s “Old Friends” (1894) conveys the deep emotion of a rugged old woodsman contemplating a massive ancient tree. Homer&#39;s expressive rendering of the man&#39;s upturned face underscores the emotional link. The composition illustrates his use of “subtractive” painting: Though Homer evidently depicted the Adirondack woodland surrounding the man and the enormous trunk, he subsequently scraped away the paint at the left of the sheet, fashioning a br ight white cloud out of the white paper&#39;s now roughened surface to emphasize the great tree&#39;s majestic presence. Having first seen this profoundly moving work when it was lent by the WAM, along with Sargent&#39;s “Muddy Alligators” and “Bathers,” to the 2017 show “American Watercolor in the Age of Homer and Sargent” at the Philadelphia Museum of Art, I can declare on seeing it this time that familiarity certainly has not bred contempt.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Scherer writes about music and the fine arts for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/watercolors-unboxed-review-worcester-sargent-homer-modigliani-lawrence-7a2421b4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/watercolors-unboxed-review-worcester-sargent-homer-modigliani-lawrence-7a2421b4<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Joseph Losey’s ‘The Servant’: That Touch of Crass]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这部 1963 年的电影改编自罗宾·毛姆的中篇小说，通过贵族与其狡猾的男仆之间摇摇欲坠的关系的镜头探讨了阶级紧张关系<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590055673424606044"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814178?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dirk Bogarde and James Fox</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Studiocanal/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590055673424606044"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">大卫·默梅尔斯坦</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 14, 2023 5:24 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joseph-loseys-the-servant-that-touch-of-crass-8558fe5b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Had Robin Maugham been less stubborn, we might not have the director Joseph Losey&#39;s serenely chilling 1963 film adaptation of Maugham&#39;s novella “The Servant.” But Maugham, a nephew of the writer W. Somerset Maugham and later a hereditary viscount, was determined to turn “The Servant,” first published in 1948, into a play and unwilling to sell the movie rights if such a deal also included those for the stage.</p><p> At first, it hardly mattered, for “The Servant,” a sly parable of class dislocation and moral rot, was initially considered unfilmable. But by the time Maugham finished his theatrical adaptation in 1958, society had changed enough for a motion picture to be contemplated.</p><p> Initially, the Wisconsin-born, Ivy League-educated Losey, exiled from Hollywood at the height of the McCarthy era for his Communist sympathies, wanted to direct Maugham&#39;s stage adaptation. But that production never materialized. And only later did Losey pursue the project for the screen. First-hand accounts differ as to how exactly Maugham&#39;s novella wound up with the winning combination of Losey as director, the already distinguished playwright Harold Pinter as screenwriter and the actor Dirk Bogarde, a matinee idol in transition, as Barrett, the title character. But such details are unimportant. The finished product was and remains one of the great British films of its decade.</p><p> And now the picture has been released in a way that befits its status, in an immensely satisfying 4K restoration on Blu-ray from the Criterion Collection, following a theatrical rerelease last year. Seasoned cineastes have long awaited this day, for Douglas Slocombe&#39;s striking black-and-white cinematography is among the movie&#39;s many outstanding features. His use of deep focus and the shots where the action is reflected in mirrors only augment the film&#39;s discomfiting vision, further signaling that nothing is quite as it first appears.</p><p> The story is uncomplicated, though no less distressing for its directness. The highborn Tony, played with effective callowness by a young James Fox, hires a manservant, the creepy but highly skilled Barrett, which finds Bogarde in the first of his career-defining roles. As Tony becomes increasingly dependent on Barrett, his connections to the outside world diminish, particularly his relationship with his fiancée, Susan, coolly played by a hard-edged Wendy Craig. A fourth character, Vera—purportedly Barrett&#39;s sister but clearly something else—helps propel Tony&#39;s presumably irreversible descent, with Sarah Miles&#39;s portrayal handily oscillating between innocent and cunning. The novella&#39;s intermittently present narrator is dispensed with entirely on screen. For, as Pinter noted, the viewer assumes that perspective.</p><p> Maugham&#39;s compulsively readable book (fewer than 75 pages) is elliptical, broadly sketched and swift-moving, whereas Losey&#39;s film is lapidary, densely packed and tense. Both plumb depths far beyond their surface details—not just class distinctions, but unblinking explorations of human nature at its least flattering.</p><p> In many ways, Losey&#39;s picture eclipses its inspiration. Maugham describes Barrett repeatedly as reptilian. But by casting the suave Bogarde, the director invests the valet with added powers of manipulation—surpassing corruption and veering toward seduction. Maugham&#39;s book merely hints at a sexual connection between master and servant, but Pinter&#39;s screenplay comes tantalizingly close to depicting it. (What happens after the final credits roll is anyone&#39;s guess.)</p><p> All of this is conveyed expertly by Losey, and made all the more effective by his use of a cramped London townhouse that he and Richard Macdonald, the production designer, furnished with obsessive care. In an especially sly nod, the house&#39;s ancestral paintings actually belonged to Maugham. The intricacy of the mise-en-scène, with its forced intimacy and inspired use of mirrors as metaphor, only heightens the action and the sting of Pinter&#39;s barbed language. In one delicious moment of foreshadowing, Barrett says to Susan: “I&#39;m afraid it&#39;s not very encouraging, Miss . 。 。 the weather forecast.”</p><p> Less often appreciated is the saxophonist and composer John Dankworth&#39;s</p>不平衡的爵士乐配乐，无缝地融合了自由精神和不祥预感。尽管它深深植根于它的时代，但它也超越了它的时代，为新生的摇摆伦敦增添了险恶的色彩。<p></p><p> At the center of “The Servant” stands an ugly truth: Humans are weak creatures, prone to temptation and even, sometimes, degradation. That, alas, is our lot. Maugham, Pinter and Losey are merely, pitilessly, holding up the looking glass.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Mermelstein, the Journal&#39;s classical music critic, also writes on film.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 21:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/joseph-loseys-the-servant-that-touch-of-crass-8558fe5b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/joseph-loseys-the-servant-that-touch-of-crass-8558fe5b<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item></channel></rss>